    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I had to remove the following jar:\ncom.ibm.icu_72.1.0.v20221115-2007.jar\nFrom my plugins directory on windows:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>C:\\Users\\USERNAME.p2\\pool\\plugins</p>\n</blockquote>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 13832502,
      "reputation" : 101,
      "user_id" : 9984969,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/OE6jI.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Nikola Pavlovic",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/9984969/nikola-pavlovic"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1696942736,
    "creation_date" : 1696942736,
    "answer_id" : 77266005,
    "question_id" : 74780857,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This might be outdated, but for anyone still looking for answers, you might want to check that you have a good &quot;com.ibm.icu_xxxxxxxxxxx.jar&quot; in your plugins dir to begin with.</p>\n<p>Recently transfered over from Windows to Linux, reconfiguring Eclipse (same version 2020-06) I encountered this error on the Linux side. Turns out, the jar in linux and windows versions are somehow a mismatch;\nCopying manually from the windows eclipse config solved my problem with said error</p>\n<p>&quot;An internal error occurred during: &quot;Requesting Java AST from selection&quot;.\ncom.ibm.icu.text.UTF16.isSurrogate(C)Z&quot;</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10203549,
      "reputation" : 1512,
      "user_id" : 7532946,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 0,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/IbtdA.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "anson",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7532946/anson"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1724053177,
    "creation_date" : 1724053177,
    "answer_id" : 78886797,
    "question_id" : 74780857,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Open Eclipse: Launch your Eclipse IDE.</p>\n<p>Access Installation Details:</p>\n<p>Go to the Eclipse menu (or Help menu on Windows/Linux).\nSelect About Eclipse IDE (or <strong>About Eclipse</strong> on older versions).\nView Installation Details:</p>\n<p>In the dialog that appears, click on the <strong>Installation Details</strong> button.</p>\n<p>find all com.ibm.icu*.jar; <br>\nremove the newest version (or rename the extension)</p>\n<p>go to the eclipse.app  <strong>eclipse/plugins/</strong> search for the jar file, delete and restart the eclipse again.</p>\n<p>It worked for me!</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 23694251,
      "reputation" : 186,
      "user_id" : 17718213,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Le5CF.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Shubham Patil",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/17718213/shubham-patil"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1762785614,
    "creation_date" : 1762785614,
    "answer_id" : 79815738,
    "question_id" : 74780857,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I found the following JAR files in the <code>&lt;Eclipse_folder&gt;/plugin</code> directory:</p>\n<p><code>com.ibm.icu_58.2.0.v20170418-1837.jar</code></p>\n<p><code>com.ibm.icu_77.1.0.jar</code></p>\n<p>I deleted <code>com.ibm.icu_77.1.0.jar</code>, and Eclipse started working fine for me.</p>\n"
  } ],
